      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(slack): opt-in flag to collapse assistant DM threads into base DM session",
        "body": "## Summary\n\nAdds `channels.slack.dm.collapseAssistantThreads` (boolean, default `false`) that, when enabled, routes all DM messages — including those wrapped in Slack's `assistant_app_thread` — into the user's base DM session instead of spawning a new `:thread:<assistantThreadTs>` suffixed session per message.\n\n## Why\n\nWhen the Slack app has the \"Agent or Assistant\" capability enabled, every inbound DM carries a unique `assistant_app_thread.thread_ts`. The current routing in `prepare-routing.ts` uses that as `canonicalThreadId` for direct messages, which `resolveThreadSessionKeys` then suffixes onto the session key. Result: every DM creates a new sibling session, fragmenting agent context across invisible threads.\n\nPer ClawSweeper's triage on #87019, the existing contract is documented and tested, so changing the default behavior is a product decision. This PR sidesteps that by making the fix opt-in: existing users see zero change; users hitting the bug can flip the flag.\n\n## Changes\n\n- New config field `dm.collapseAssistantThreads` (default `false`)\n- `prepare-routing.ts` gates the `isDirectMessage → assistantThreadId` path on the flag, reading it from the **merged Slack account config** (`account.dm`) — mirroring how `resolveSlackReplyToMode` reads `account.dm.replyToMode`. This honors both root `channels.slack.dm` and account-scoped `channels.slack.accounts.<id>.dm`.\n- `accounts.ts`: add `\"dm\"` to Slack's `nestedObjectKeys` so root and account `dm` config **deep-merge**. Without this, an account-level `dm` block that sets any other key shallow-replaces the whole root `dm` object, and a documented global `collapseAssistantThreads: true` would silently stop applying for that account.\n- Regenerated `bundled-channel-config-metadata.generated.ts` so the new key is present (`config:channels:check` passes)\n- Three regression tests in `prepare.thread-session-key.test.ts` driven through the real `resolveSlackAccount()` resolver: root-scoped (back-compat), account-scoped, and **global flag + unrelated account `dm` override** (the inheritance case)\n- Docs update in `docs/channels/slack.md`\n\n## Review follow-ups addressed (ClawSweeper)\n\n- **[P1] Read the flag from the merged account config.** Routing previously read only `ctx.cfg.channels?.slack?.dm`; an account-scoped opt-in validated but was a silent no-op. Now reads `account.dm?.collapseAssistantThreads` (merged config), with account-level coverage.\n- **[P1] Preserve the global flag through account `dm` overrides.** `mergeSlackAccountConfig` only deep-merged `nestedObjectKeys` (formerly just `botLoopProtection`), so an account `dm` override shallow-replaced root `dm` and dropped a global `collapseAssistantThreads`. Added `\"dm\"` to `nestedObjectKeys` and a focused root-flag-plus-account-override regression test.\n- **[P1] Regenerate bundled channel config metadata.** Done; `config:channels:check` is green.\n\n## Verification\n\n- `extension-slack` routing suite: **18/18 pass** (`prepare.thread-session-key.test.ts`)\n- `tsgo:extensions` (prod types) and `tsgo:extensions:test` both pass\n- `config:channels:check` passes after regenerating bundled metadata\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\n**Behavior or issue addressed:** Slack's \"Agent or Assistant\" capability wraps each DM in a unique `assistant_app_thread.thread_ts`, so consecutive DMs from one user resolve to different `:thread:<ts>` OpenClaw sessions and fragment context (#87019). With `dm.collapseAssistantThreads: true`, assistant DMs collapse onto the single base DM session.\n\n**Real environment tested:** Checked out this PR head (`f11bb59`) in a real OpenClaw working tree on macOS, Node v22.22.3, pnpm 11.2.2, deps installed via `pnpm install --frozen-lockfile`. Drove the **actual compiled routing module** (`extensions/slack/src/monitor/message-handler/prepare-routing.ts`) and the real account resolver (`extensions/slack/src/accounts.ts`) — the same functions the live Slack plugin invokes for every inbound message — via `node --import tsx`. No mocks or stubs.\n\n**Exact steps or command run after this patch:** the commands below were run after applying the patch; the last one drives the real patched routing module with two consecutive assistant DMs from the same user under three configs (flag absent, root flag on, account-scoped flag on).\n\n```\npnpm install --frozen-lockfile\nnode scripts/run-vitest.mjs run extensions/slack/src/monitor/message-handler/prepare.thread-session-key.test.ts\npnpm tsgo:extensions && pnpm tsgo:extensions:test\npnpm run config:channels:check\nnode --import tsx proof-87667.mts\n```\n\n**Evidence after fix:** Live console output from running the real patched routing code on Node (redacted user/team/channel ids):\n\n```\n=== BASELINE: flag absent (current default, reproduces #87019) ===\n  DM #1 (assistant thread_ts=1770408530.000100) -> agent:main:main:thread:1770408530.000100\n  DM #2 (assistant thread_ts=1770409999.000100) -> agent:main:main:thread:1770409999.000100\n  account.dm.collapseAssistantThreads = undefined\n  distinct session keys across 2 DMs: 2 (FANNED OUT)\n\n=== FIX A: root channels.slack.dm.collapseAssistantThreads = true ===\n  DM #1 (assistant thread_ts=1770408530.000100) -> agent:main:main\n  DM #2 (assistant thread_ts=1770409999.000100) -> agent:main:main\n  account.dm.collapseAssistantThreads = true\n  distinct session keys across 2 DMs: 1 (COLLAPSED)\n\n=== FIX B: account-scoped channels.slack.accounts.default.dm.collapseAssistantThreads = true ===\n  DM #1 (assistant thread_ts=1770408530.000100) -> agent:main:main\n  DM #2 (assistant thread_ts=1770409999.000100) -> agent:main:main\n  account.dm.collapseAssistantThreads = true\n  distinct session keys across 2 DMs: 1 (COLLAPSED)\n\n=== FIX C: global dm.collapseAssistantThreads=true + account dm:{policy:open} override (inheritance) ===\n  DM #1 (assistant thread_ts=1770408530.000100) -> agent:main:main\n  DM #2 (assistant thread_ts=1770409999.000100) -> agent:main:main\n  account.dm.collapseAssistantThreads = true\n  distinct session keys across 2 DMs: 1 (COLLAPSED)\n```\n\nFor FIX C, temporarily reverting the `nestedObjectKeys` change (i.e. dropping `\"dm\"`) and re-running shows the regression the fix prevents — the account `dm` override drops the global flag and DMs fan out again:\n\n```\n=== FIX C: global dm.collapseAssistantThreads=true + account dm:{policy:open} override (inheritance) ===\n  DM #1 (assistant thread_ts=1770408530.000100) -> agent:main:main:thread:1770408530.000100\n  DM #2 (assistant thread_ts=1770409999.000100) -> agent:main:main:thread:1770409999.000100\n  account.dm.collapseAssistantThreads = undefined\n  distinct session keys across 2 DMs: 2 (FANNED OUT)\n```\n\nVitest run (18/18):\n\n```\n ✓  extension-slack  extensions/slack/src/monitor/message-handler/prepare.thread-session-key.test.ts (18 tests) 7ms\n Test Files  1 passed (1)\n      Tests  18 passed (18)\n```\n\n**Observed result after fix:** With the flag absent (current default), the two consecutive assistant DMs resolve to **two distinct** thread-scoped session keys — the #87019 fan-out, reproduced. With the flag set at root (`channels.slack.dm`), account scope (`channels.slack.accounts.default.dm`), **or** root with an unrelated account `dm` override (FIX C), both DMs resolve to the **same single** base DM session key with no `:thread:` suffix. FIX B was a silent no-op before the merged-`account.dm` read; FIX C was a silent no-op before `\"dm\"` was added to `nestedObjectKeys` — the temporary-revert capture above confirms both now collapse correctly.\n\n**What was not tested:** This harness exercises the routing/session-key layer directly (the only layer this PR changes), so the session-key prefix prints as `agent:main:main` rather than `agent:main:slack:direct:<user>` — the full agent-route + Slack socket transport is not wired in this standalone capture, only the thread-collapse logic under test. A redacted live-workspace capture of the original fan-out on `@openclaw/slack@2026.5.18` is being sourced from a maintainer running the Agent capability and can be added if desired; the gate-relevant after-fix behavior is fully demonstrated above.\n\nFixes #87019\n",
